I"¨<p>Just like <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memory-is-like-a-manuscript">organic memory</a> induces <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/how-can-routine-cell-replacement-permit-psychological-continuity">a sense of identity</a>, so does <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/social-data-harvesting-is-malicious-crowdsourcing">collective memory</a> induce a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/similar-cultural-embedding-predicts-manifold-alignment">cultural identity</a>. Fixed <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/written-word-is-a-proxy-for-thought">written</a> identity increases inertia, just like memory implants might for people.</p>
